Hartbreakers only really does one thing (100% vegan fried chicken sandwiches) but they do it so well that anything else would be superfluous. Their vegan fried chicken is crispy and expertly seasoned, the buns are just the right amount of crunchy, and the various sauces I've had are almost impossible to adequately describe. My favorite thing on the menu is the Firebird, but honestly I think I could order an item at random off the menu here and still be delighted. There are a few sides, but the sandwiches are filling enough that you probably won't want one unless you're sharing with someone else. The drink selection is fairly minimal - a few fancy sodas, not a whole lot else. There's no desserts at all as far as I know. Prices are pretty normal for this part of Brooklyn at $13-$15 for a sandwich and $5-$7 for a side.

Really wanted to give them 3 stars but we need more vegan representation so I gave 4. This is a new place and it has all the right vibes but I wish the food was better. My crew and I order a bunch of different platters. I can’t speak for their food but I had some of the the chickn’ Tenders and Dynamite fries.  My initial disappointment was with the Jalopeño-cilantro aioli sauce(thought it’d taste more like jalapeños or at least spicy in some way but it was bland. It seemed to be going for a cheesy appeal but fell short and was more doughy to me). The ranch one was also on the bland side. These I had ordered for my Chickn’ Tenders which would have been good themselves because they had a good consistency but they were overly salted. The sauces just didn’t seem to pair with the Chikn Tenders despite them having the opposite flavor issue(bland vs overly salted).  My waffle fries was smother in the same Jalopeño-cilantro aioli which made me sad. This was causing most of my waffle fries to come out soggy when they arrived to the table. Taking away any chance I could of salvage the fries to make this meal work. It was soo much sauce that it took away from the enjoyment of my fries. (If the sauce had tasted a bit better I might have not minded as much) I scrapped off most of the sauce to at least eat the waffle fries but even the ones that hadn’t been sauced were soggy from the condensation of the fries above. Needless to say I didn’t finish or take the fries “to go” though I took the chickn Tenders home to doctor up a sauce of my own that would be complimentary. It’s be one thing if I was the only person that was disappointed with the food, but my crew were as well.  We need more vegan restaurant trying to make it so I do apologize if this review seems rough, however in this day and age where Vegan places are popping out of the woodwork, “flavor or taste” is important also. It is what should be the new definition of good vegan food versus the misconceptions of what non vegans currently believe it to be.
